WEBVTT

00:00.775 --> 00:01.941
[TV static drones]

00:01.941 --> 00:04.877
[bright tone]

00:04.877 --> 00:07.814
<i>[spirited orchestral music]</i>

00:07.814 --> 00:15.019
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:40.275 --> 01:43.377
<i>[cheerful music]</i>

01:43.377 --> 01:50.419
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:50.306 --> 02:53.713
Are you sure this isn't
too much for you, Agnes?

02:53.713 --> 02:55.514
We should have ordered
the carriage.

02:55.514 --> 02:57.316
All my life, I've walked
to church on Easter morning.

02:57.316 --> 02:59.151
Why should I stop now?

02:59.151 --> 03:01.287
Because we're getting older.

03:01.287 --> 03:03.892
You may be getting older.
I am not.

03:05.693 --> 03:07.159
How long
will you be in Newport?

03:07.159 --> 03:08.593
Only a few days this time.

03:08.593 --> 03:09.996
Larry says
the house is finished,

03:09.996 --> 03:12.164
and I want to make sure
that it is.

03:12.164 --> 03:13.332
Well, I hope
it will take your mind

03:13.332 --> 03:14.967
off that other business.

03:14.967 --> 03:16.402
I hate to see you upset.

03:16.402 --> 03:17.636
Nothing will take my mind

03:17.636 --> 03:19.605
off that "other business,"
as you call it.

03:19.605 --> 03:21.607
As long as we have no box
at the Academy,

03:21.607 --> 03:23.376
we are not in the front rank
of society,

03:23.376 --> 03:24.905
whatever we may pretend.

03:24.905 --> 03:26.078
That's what
Carrie Astor says.

03:26.078 --> 03:27.246
Well, she should know.

03:27.246 --> 03:28.614
Her mother will have
been consulted,

03:28.614 --> 03:30.282
and she must have decided
to keep us out.

03:30.282 --> 03:31.851
The Academy must have
a list of applicants

03:31.851 --> 03:33.219
as long as your arm.

03:33.219 --> 03:34.888
And I'm sure
Mrs. Astor tried to help.

03:34.888 --> 03:35.888
Are you?
[scoffs]

03:35.888 --> 03:37.760
I'm not.

03:40.996 --> 03:42.896
What do you see?

03:42.896 --> 03:45.902
I'd forgotten how beautiful
Philadelphia was.

03:47.335 --> 03:49.201
I hope we're not
going to be late.

03:49.201 --> 03:50.737
The church isn't far.

03:50.737 --> 03:52.005
So you know?

03:52.005 --> 03:55.278
When I was in school,
we'd visit for some events.

03:56.744 --> 03:58.711
It was nice of Mr. Spring
to invite us.

03:58.711 --> 04:01.014
I suppose none of this
is easy for them.

04:01.014 --> 04:03.177
Of course not.

04:03.177 --> 04:05.684
But the Spring family
has asked us to join them

04:05.684 --> 04:09.723
in their grief for Easter,
so that is what we shall do.

04:09.723 --> 04:14.894
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:14.894 --> 04:19.794
[indistinct chatter]

04:19.794 --> 04:21.567
<i>Après vous, monsieur.</i>

04:21.567 --> 04:25.138
Or should I say,
"You first, mister"?

04:25.138 --> 04:26.840
[laughter]
- It does not offend me

04:26.840 --> 04:28.573
that I am a source of humor
to you all.

04:28.573 --> 04:31.510
I confess, I would like to know
how long it must go on.

04:31.510 --> 04:33.479
Until it stops
making us smile.

04:33.479 --> 04:36.215
Mr. Gordon pretended
to be French to get a job.

04:36.215 --> 04:37.549
Is that a crime?

04:37.549 --> 04:40.486
Not a crime,
but quite a good joke.

04:40.486 --> 04:42.956
If the mistress can accept
that her chef is from Kansas,

04:42.956 --> 04:44.023
surely we can.

04:44.023 --> 04:45.424
If she admits it at all,

04:45.424 --> 04:47.326
I bet it's through
gritted teeth.

04:47.326 --> 04:49.996
Or should we say,
"par les dents serrées"?

04:49.996 --> 04:52.699
[laughter]

04:52.699 --> 04:54.233
[groans]

04:54.233 --> 04:57.706
We have a big dinner tonight.
[indistinct]

04:58.907 --> 05:00.907
Hello.

05:00.907 --> 05:02.442
Miss Weber, isn't it?

05:02.442 --> 05:03.943
How do you know my name?

05:03.943 --> 05:05.878
I asked one of your footmen.

05:05.878 --> 05:07.346
I'm Jack Trotter.

05:07.346 --> 05:10.049
I work for Mrs. Van Rhijn
across the street.

05:10.049 --> 05:13.652
Then happy Easter,
Mr. Trotter.

05:13.652 --> 05:16.388
I was thinking you might like
to meet up some day,

05:16.388 --> 05:18.157
maybe have a cup of coffee.

05:18.157 --> 05:20.359
We're off
to Newport tomorrow.

05:20.359 --> 05:22.561
- For long?
- Only till next Monday.

05:22.561 --> 05:24.430
But we'll go back soon
for the season.

05:24.430 --> 05:26.999
When you get home, maybe
we could arrange something

05:26.999 --> 05:28.768
before you're gone again.

05:28.768 --> 05:30.539
I'd like that.

05:32.675 --> 05:35.074
How pretty they've made it.

05:35.074 --> 05:36.509
There's Mrs. Russell.

05:36.509 --> 05:39.345
Oh, happy Easter.
To all of you.

05:39.345 --> 05:41.148
Ada, come sit down.

05:41.148 --> 05:45.318
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:45.318 --> 05:48.491
[women whispering]

05:50.392 --> 05:51.624
- Agnes.
- Lina

05:51.624 --> 05:53.160
Ada.

05:53.160 --> 05:59.363
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:00.997 --> 06:02.435
Oh, I meant to tell you,

06:02.435 --> 06:04.637
I've had a letter
from Dashiell Montgomery.

06:04.637 --> 06:06.471
- Oh, how is he?
- Who is he?

06:06.471 --> 06:08.675
- A nephew of my late husband.
- Arnold.

06:08.675 --> 06:10.443
Were you on first name terms?

06:10.443 --> 06:12.178
We weren't, and I was his wife.

06:12.178 --> 06:13.612
What's Dashiell up to?

06:13.612 --> 06:15.381
Well, it seems
he tired of Washington

06:15.381 --> 06:17.517
and has moved back to New York
with his daughter.

06:17.517 --> 06:20.019
Oh, poor motherless girl.

06:20.019 --> 06:21.287
Motherless?

06:21.287 --> 06:23.489
Dashiell's wife died
very young.

06:23.489 --> 06:25.791
Frances must be about 14 now.

06:25.791 --> 06:27.361
I'll invite them
for some tea,

06:27.361 --> 06:28.928
maybe next Thursday.

06:28.928 --> 06:30.129
Not Thursday.

06:30.129 --> 06:31.567
Why not?

06:32.601 --> 06:34.834
No reason, really.

06:34.834 --> 06:37.036
But I'm usually rather busy
on Thursdays.

06:37.036 --> 06:40.406
Oh.

06:40.406 --> 06:44.543
As we celebrate
the resurrection of our savior,

06:44.543 --> 06:48.714
we know the Lord is close
to the brokenhearted.

06:48.714 --> 06:52.318
And we pray for those
in our congregation,

06:52.318 --> 06:56.021
the sick, the lonely,
the bereaved.

06:56.021 --> 07:00.492
And we ask continued prayer
for Samuel Spring

07:00.492 --> 07:02.561
since the death of his wife
and son

07:02.561 --> 07:05.231
who was blessed
with two mothers,

07:05.231 --> 07:08.267
one of whom is here today.

07:08.267 --> 07:10.203
Our prayers are with you all.

07:10.203 --> 07:11.771
<i>[soft music]</i>

07:11.771 --> 07:15.842
Easter is a time of renewal.

07:15.842 --> 07:17.810
It is through
the miracle of Easter

07:17.810 --> 07:20.512
that our savior gives us
new life.

07:20.512 --> 07:24.483
Today, we declare
our sublime and unshaken faith

07:24.483 --> 07:27.820
that Christ did
truly rise from death

07:27.820 --> 07:31.190
and that God,
having raised Him up,

07:31.190 --> 07:34.394
shall also raise us up
with Him.

07:34.394 --> 07:35.929
Please rise.

07:35.929 --> 07:39.498
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:39.498 --> 07:43.337
Let us ask, O God,
that our hearts may be light

07:43.337 --> 07:45.605
with heavenly hope.

07:45.605 --> 07:47.741
It may not happen
in this world,

07:47.741 --> 07:51.343
but it will happen
in the sweet hereafter

07:51.343 --> 07:54.180
when we shall rise again

07:54.180 --> 07:56.816
and be made like unto Christ

07:56.816 --> 08:01.120
in His eternal
and glorious Kingdom.

08:01.120 --> 08:04.627
Amen.
all: Amen.

08:06.395 --> 08:09.296
<i>[light music]</i>

08:09.296 --> 08:10.730
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:10.730 --> 08:12.965
- Lovely to have you.
- Thank you.

08:12.965 --> 08:15.801
- Happy Easter.
- Happy Easter to you.

08:15.801 --> 08:18.204
I thought he did well.
The new rector.

08:18.204 --> 08:20.106
He kept the sermon short,
which is something.

08:20.106 --> 08:22.574
Oh, look. He's over there.
Shall we say hello?

08:22.574 --> 08:24.009
You could leave it
for another time.

08:24.009 --> 08:26.845
Excuse me.

08:26.845 --> 08:30.415
I know exactly who you are.
Mrs. Van Rhijn and Miss Brook.

08:30.415 --> 08:31.918
They've told me all about you.

08:31.918 --> 08:33.853
You mustn't believe
everything you hear.

08:33.853 --> 08:36.555
And this is our niece,
Miss Marian Brook

08:36.555 --> 08:38.358
and Mrs. Van Rhijn's son, Oscar.

08:38.358 --> 08:39.726
Pleasure.

08:39.726 --> 08:41.160
That was a lovely sermon.

08:41.160 --> 08:42.327
I hope so.

08:42.327 --> 08:44.997
Half the battle is not to put
the congregation to sleep.

08:44.997 --> 08:46.433
[laughter]

08:46.433 --> 08:49.202
Mr. Russell.

08:49.202 --> 08:50.569
I thought I might see you here.

08:50.569 --> 08:51.971
Happy Easter to you,
Mr. Tritton.

08:51.971 --> 08:54.373
I hear you're having
some union difficulties

08:54.373 --> 08:56.242
in Pittsburgh.
- You could say that.

08:56.242 --> 08:58.378
I ask because
we're going through something

08:58.378 --> 08:59.711
similar in Cleveland.

08:59.711 --> 09:02.481
And of course, Jay Gould is
having trouble too.

09:02.481 --> 09:05.318
They say membership
of the Knights of Labor

09:05.318 --> 09:07.320
is in the hundreds
of thousands now.

09:07.320 --> 09:09.055
Never mind
the Knights of Labor.

09:09.055 --> 09:11.057
We must deal
with the steelworkers.

09:11.057 --> 09:13.259
They've elected a new leader,
a man called Henderson.

09:13.259 --> 09:15.728
And I'm afraid he seems
to know what he's doing.

09:15.728 --> 09:17.597
The only thing
worse than a union man

09:17.597 --> 09:19.631
is a clever union man.

09:19.631 --> 09:21.468
We ought to get
some of the owners together.

09:21.468 --> 09:22.601
Gould, Morgan.

09:22.601 --> 09:25.204
Billy Vanderbilt,
if he'd come.

09:25.204 --> 09:27.540
- Shall we go?
- Of course.

09:27.540 --> 09:29.709
We'll be in touch.

09:29.709 --> 09:31.677
How are you settling
into the city?

09:31.677 --> 09:34.080
Well, New York is
very different from Boston.

09:34.080 --> 09:37.511
It's the little things I miss--
old haunts, familiar food.

09:37.511 --> 09:39.284
New York cuisine isn't
meeting your standards?

09:39.284 --> 09:40.785
Oh, quite the opposite,

09:40.785 --> 09:43.389
though I am still searching
for an authentic bowl

09:43.389 --> 09:44.724
of New England clam chowder.

09:44.724 --> 09:47.259
[laughter]
- Well, I hope you find it.

09:47.259 --> 09:48.494
But you're managing?

09:48.494 --> 09:51.097
I survived
the Easter service today.

09:51.097 --> 09:52.598
And my first wedding
is this week.

09:52.598 --> 09:54.466
- Ah.
- So I feel I'm getting there.

09:54.466 --> 09:56.636
May we hear
who is to be married?

09:56.636 --> 10:00.006
Uh, Miss Bingham
and Mr. Raikes.

10:00.006 --> 10:01.273
Do you know them,
by any chance?

10:01.273 --> 10:02.274
- No.
- A little.

10:02.274 --> 10:03.279
- Not really.
- Yes.

10:05.480 --> 10:06.645
We should go.

10:06.645 --> 10:08.480
We mustn't keep the rector
all to ourselves.

10:08.480 --> 10:10.920
Happy Easter.
both: Happy Easter.

10:13.489 --> 10:15.088
[exhales]

10:15.088 --> 10:17.090
Agnes, slow down.

10:17.090 --> 10:18.324
We're not in a race.

10:18.324 --> 10:19.391
Speak for yourself.

10:19.391 --> 10:21.160
I couldn't get away
fast enough.

10:21.160 --> 10:24.163
Mama, I think
I'll say goodbye here.

10:24.163 --> 10:25.364
I need a cab.

10:25.364 --> 10:27.100
But you'll be back
for dinner?

10:27.100 --> 10:28.468
I will.

10:28.468 --> 10:31.438
<i>[light quirky music]</i>

10:31.438 --> 10:35.408
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:35.408 --> 10:38.778
- I hope you'll come.
- I mean to.

10:38.778 --> 10:40.512
Are you going
to Mrs. Rutherford's ball?

10:40.512 --> 10:42.615
I'm quite surprised
I've been invited.

10:42.615 --> 10:43.883
With three bachelor sons?

10:43.883 --> 10:45.819
Mother says she'll have
every heiress in New York

10:45.819 --> 10:48.821
on the dance floor.

10:48.821 --> 10:50.756
I've been meaning
to ask you about your hat.

10:50.756 --> 10:52.091
Isn't it lovely?

10:52.091 --> 10:53.893
How did you enjoy
the service?

10:53.893 --> 10:56.162
I thought it was perfect.

10:56.162 --> 10:59.198
[indistinct chatter]

10:59.198 --> 11:02.034
Yes, I do too.

11:02.034 --> 11:05.071
[laughter]

11:05.071 --> 11:08.041
<i>[somber music]</i>

11:08.041 --> 11:15.051
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:19.688 --> 11:23.656
It's been six months.

11:23.656 --> 11:25.892
I should have written sooner,

11:25.892 --> 11:27.459
as soon as I heard
you were looking for me,

11:27.459 --> 11:32.326
but by then, they were gone,
and I wasn't thinking straight.

11:32.326 --> 11:34.901
It's good of you to come today.

11:34.901 --> 11:38.741
We wanted to,
to learn about him.

11:42.277 --> 11:45.078
"A loved
and loving little boy."

11:45.078 --> 11:48.380
And so he was.

11:48.380 --> 11:51.083
I wish I'd known him.

11:51.083 --> 11:53.119
You're coming home with me,

11:53.119 --> 11:55.921
so I can show you his room
and his toys.

11:55.921 --> 11:59.091
And maybe you'll feel
that you do know him a little.

11:59.091 --> 12:00.796
I hope so.

12:09.204 --> 12:10.339
Mother.

12:17.112 --> 12:18.944
Were we right
to bring her here?

12:18.944 --> 12:22.851
She deserves the full story
of his short and dear life.

12:24.319 --> 12:27.186
Dorothy, please.

12:27.186 --> 12:29.889
You can't blame me
for scarlet fever.

12:29.889 --> 12:31.658
I can blame you
that we weren't here

12:31.658 --> 12:34.193
before the fever struck.

12:34.193 --> 12:36.862
If you had contacted
Miss Wade sooner,

12:36.862 --> 12:40.169
our boy might be alive today.

12:45.507 --> 12:50.310
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:50.310 --> 12:53.347
[laughter]

12:53.347 --> 12:56.316
[indistinct chatter]

12:56.316 --> 13:02.325
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:03.859 --> 13:05.625
Hey.
[whistles]

13:05.625 --> 13:07.326
Give me another.

13:07.326 --> 13:10.430
We're celebrating!
[indistinct chatter]

13:10.430 --> 13:12.065
It's on him.

13:12.065 --> 13:19.108
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:36.992 --> 13:40.096
[sobbing softly]

13:47.902 --> 13:49.236
Did he like the room?

13:49.236 --> 13:50.637
Mm-hmm.

13:50.637 --> 13:53.640
<i>[tender music]</i>

13:53.640 --> 13:57.710
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:57.710 --> 13:59.412
Did he enjoy his life?

13:59.412 --> 14:01.347
He was a happy child,

14:01.347 --> 14:04.750
always laughing,
always full of fun.

14:04.750 --> 14:06.453
We wouldn't have
stopped you seeing him.

14:06.453 --> 14:08.555
I hope you believe that.

14:08.555 --> 14:11.791
Don't be too nice to me.

14:11.791 --> 14:14.594
I'd have taken him away.

14:14.594 --> 14:15.895
I'd have fought the adoption

14:15.895 --> 14:17.930
and I would have taken him
with me if I could.

14:17.930 --> 14:19.759
I wish you had.

14:19.759 --> 14:21.233
It might have saved him
if you'd gotten him

14:21.233 --> 14:23.303
out of the city
before the fever came.

14:23.303 --> 14:24.571
Don't say that.

14:24.571 --> 14:27.176
Or we'll all go mad.

14:29.445 --> 14:31.480
[laughs tearfully]

14:34.616 --> 14:35.882
Oh.

14:35.882 --> 14:37.650
Keep it.

14:37.650 --> 14:39.919
I mean it.

14:39.919 --> 14:42.191
He loved his bear.

14:43.391 --> 14:46.162
His mother should have
his favorite toy.

14:48.497 --> 14:50.730
His other mother.

14:50.730 --> 14:52.632
She loved him, you know.

14:52.632 --> 14:54.967
My Carlotta, she loved him.

14:54.967 --> 14:57.670
And she nursed him,
and she caught the fever,

14:57.670 --> 15:00.072
and she died with him.

15:00.072 --> 15:03.476
Shall we go downstairs
for our Easter dinner?

15:03.476 --> 15:05.248
I have a gift for you.

15:07.149 --> 15:11.050
Here's a photograph,
if it wouldn't be too painful.

15:11.050 --> 15:13.118
- Don't you want to keep it?
- [sobbing]

15:13.118 --> 15:16.022
I have one of them
taken later with my wife,

15:16.022 --> 15:19.625
not long before they died,
just as I remember them.

15:19.625 --> 15:22.061
I appreciate your kindness.

15:22.061 --> 15:25.765
So do I. I mean it.

15:25.765 --> 15:28.400
We share a child,

15:28.400 --> 15:32.705
a bond no one could
even try to understand.

15:32.705 --> 15:34.474
That's why we came.

15:34.474 --> 15:35.675
[bell ringing]

15:35.675 --> 15:37.613
Please come to the table.

15:38.914 --> 15:42.018
[children giggling]

15:43.952 --> 15:45.485
Coming!

15:45.485 --> 15:49.589
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:49.589 --> 15:50.724
Mrs. Scott.

15:50.724 --> 15:51.924
Slowly, girl.

15:51.924 --> 15:54.630
The food's not going anywhere.

15:56.331 --> 15:59.465
- [breathes deeply]
- Let's join hands, everyone.

15:59.465 --> 16:03.106
Mother, would you like
to say grace?

16:06.340 --> 16:08.207
How was your service,
Bridget?

16:08.207 --> 16:09.842
Or should I call it mass?

16:09.842 --> 16:11.443
Good.
I like St. Patrick's.

16:11.443 --> 16:13.112
The new cathedral is
a credit to the city,

16:13.112 --> 16:14.348
I'll give you that.

16:14.348 --> 16:15.281
How was yours?

16:15.281 --> 16:17.116
I enjoyed it,
with all the ladies

16:17.116 --> 16:18.750
showing off
the latest fashions.

16:18.750 --> 16:21.888
I'm not sure what that
has to do with holy worship.

16:21.888 --> 16:23.989
What were you saying
to Miss Weber?

16:23.989 --> 16:26.058
- Um...
- When did you see her?

16:26.058 --> 16:28.194
She was at church with
the other Russell servants.

16:28.194 --> 16:31.365
<i>[light plucky music]</i>

16:31.365 --> 16:36.435
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:36.435 --> 16:39.105
Don't you ever get tired
of that wretched tapestry?

16:39.105 --> 16:42.609
You're like Penelope waiting
for Odysseus to get home.

16:42.609 --> 16:44.043
Aunt Ada likes needlework.

16:44.043 --> 16:45.444
I like ice cream.

16:45.444 --> 16:48.848
That doesn't mean I eat it
24 hours a day.

16:48.848 --> 16:50.415
Ah.
- You rang, ma'am?

16:50.415 --> 16:52.451
Yes, we can't wait
for Mr. Oscar any longer.

16:52.451 --> 16:54.253
I don't know
what's happened to him.

16:54.253 --> 16:55.889
But if you can tell Mrs. Bauer,

16:55.889 --> 16:57.691
we'll have dinner
as soon as she's ready.

16:57.691 --> 16:59.726
Very good, ma'am.

16:59.726 --> 17:01.628
[sighs]
[door creaks]

17:01.628 --> 17:03.029
Oh.

17:03.029 --> 17:05.168
I expect that's him now.

17:06.702 --> 17:08.668
- [groaning]
- [gasps]

17:08.668 --> 17:10.202
Oscar!

17:10.202 --> 17:11.904
- My God!
- Oscar, what happened?

17:11.904 --> 17:13.873
- Who has done this?
- I'm sorry.

17:13.873 --> 17:15.241
I--I haven't changed.
I just--

17:15.241 --> 17:17.243
[all gasp]
- Oscar!

17:17.243 --> 17:19.445
Bannister, help me get
Mr. Oscar up to the Blue Room,

17:19.445 --> 17:20.914
and find an old nightshirt.
- Yes, ma'am.

17:20.914 --> 17:22.949
Marian, send John
for Dr. Lewis.

17:22.949 --> 17:25.250
Ada, do we have
any bandages or salves?

17:25.250 --> 17:26.986
Yes, I think
they're in the kitchen.

17:26.986 --> 17:28.722
I'll fetch them.

17:28.722 --> 17:30.457
Can you see?

17:30.457 --> 17:32.959
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

17:32.959 --> 17:34.326
John.

17:34.326 --> 17:36.261
- Yes?
- Fetch Dr. Lewis.

17:36.261 --> 17:38.363
And when you've done that,
go to Mr. Oscar's rooms

17:38.363 --> 17:40.166
and tell his man to give you
what he'll need for tonight.

17:40.166 --> 17:42.101
- Why? What happened?
- Mr. Oscar has been attacked.

17:42.101 --> 17:43.135
- [gasps]
- What?

17:43.135 --> 17:44.769
I need whatever bandages
and creams we have here.

17:44.769 --> 17:46.740
- I know where they are.
- What do you mean attacked?

17:46.740 --> 17:47.835
What I said.

17:47.835 --> 17:50.009
He's been beaten
and I daresay robbed.

17:50.009 --> 17:51.545
Here we are.

17:51.545 --> 17:57.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:57.016 --> 17:58.618
How are you feeling?

17:58.618 --> 18:00.319
Much better, thank you.

18:00.319 --> 18:01.921
Then we must send
for the police.

18:01.921 --> 18:04.157
No, no.
Not the police.

18:04.157 --> 18:07.126
Why not, when you've been
set upon in the street?

18:07.126 --> 18:08.260
I have nothing to tell them.

18:08.260 --> 18:09.596
I didn't see his face.

18:09.596 --> 18:11.030
It all happened so fast.

18:11.030 --> 18:12.998
And I don't want to be
a story in the papers.

18:12.998 --> 18:14.867
Well, I can understand that.

18:14.867 --> 18:17.036
But you really have
no evidence?

18:17.036 --> 18:19.271
My mind is a complete blank.

18:19.271 --> 18:21.440
And you did nothing
to provoke him?

18:21.440 --> 18:22.809
Why do you say such a thing?

18:22.809 --> 18:23.904
Because I know you.

18:23.904 --> 18:26.179
I've watched you be
reckless and rude.

18:26.179 --> 18:28.047
Why were you
walking the streets, anyway?

18:28.047 --> 18:30.182
Why didn't you hail a cab?
[bell ringing]

18:30.182 --> 18:32.218
That'll be Dr. Lewis.

18:32.218 --> 18:33.756
I'll go down.

18:36.257 --> 18:38.561
She's just upset.

18:43.164 --> 18:45.197
What you need is rest.

18:45.197 --> 18:48.095
When Dr. Lewis is gone,
try to sleep.

18:48.095 --> 18:50.203
Ring the bell if you need
something in the night.

18:50.203 --> 18:52.237
I'll hear it.

18:52.237 --> 18:53.806
You've missed your vocation.

18:53.806 --> 18:56.776
<i>[light music]</i>

18:56.776 --> 18:57.810
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:57.810 --> 19:01.380
[knock at door]

19:01.380 --> 19:04.183
- How is he?
- Settled.

19:04.183 --> 19:06.118
But you were right
about his needing sleep.

19:06.118 --> 19:08.654
He'll feel better
in the morning.

19:08.654 --> 19:09.789
What a business.

19:09.789 --> 19:11.323
Yes.

19:11.323 --> 19:14.961
But I really came in
to ask how you were feeling.

19:14.961 --> 19:16.162
What do you mean?

19:16.162 --> 19:20.200
When the new rector told us
about Mr. Raikes' marriage.

19:20.200 --> 19:23.406
Oh, that.

19:25.573 --> 19:29.745
It was a little bit
of a shock, but I'm fine.

19:31.212 --> 19:33.179
Or I will be.
- Good.

19:33.179 --> 19:35.282
Because you have so much
to look forward to.

19:35.282 --> 19:37.284
I'm sure of it.

19:37.284 --> 19:40.454
<i>[somber music]</i>

19:40.454 --> 19:43.756
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:43.756 --> 19:45.828
I did love him.

19:47.796 --> 19:50.096
I'm glad you used
the past tense.

19:50.096 --> 19:53.569
It helps to accept that a thing
is finished and done with.

19:56.137 --> 20:00.907
The question is, what's next?

20:00.907 --> 20:02.541
The right man
will come along.

20:02.541 --> 20:05.711
But I don't just want
a husband, Aunt Ada.

20:05.711 --> 20:07.780
And anyway,
who says he'll come along?

20:07.780 --> 20:10.016
He doesn't always.

20:10.016 --> 20:11.117
That's true.

20:11.117 --> 20:13.719
He never came for me.

20:13.719 --> 20:16.489
But I was very shy
when I was your age,

20:16.489 --> 20:20.092
with so much less to offer.

20:20.092 --> 20:21.994
It would have taken
someone rare

20:21.994 --> 20:24.196
to look inside my shell.

20:24.196 --> 20:28.034
If he didn't,
it was his loss.

20:28.034 --> 20:31.605
- Good night.
- Good night.

20:31.605 --> 20:33.673
Sleep well.

20:33.673 --> 20:35.803
And dream of all
the wonderful things

20:35.803 --> 20:36.976
that are waiting to happen.

20:36.976 --> 20:38.311
[both laugh]

20:38.311 --> 20:41.515
<i>[bright music]</i>

20:41.515 --> 20:44.618
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:44.618 --> 20:47.587
[dog barking]

20:47.587 --> 20:54.597
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:07.441 --> 21:09.274
How did you know my size?

21:09.274 --> 21:10.710
Mr. White was the one
who found it.

21:10.710 --> 21:12.211
Are you familiar
with the house?

21:12.211 --> 21:13.412
Not really.

21:13.412 --> 21:15.581
It was built
about 30 years ago,

21:15.581 --> 21:18.985
and I believe it was
quite social at the start.

21:18.985 --> 21:20.519
But for the past decade,

21:20.519 --> 21:22.421
it was owned
by a quiet old lady

21:22.421 --> 21:24.891
from Milwaukee
who did not entertain.

21:24.891 --> 21:26.425
So for most people here,
it's going to be

21:26.425 --> 21:27.927
a new house on their rounds?

21:27.927 --> 21:29.128
Indeed it will.

21:29.128 --> 21:30.596
[chuckles]

21:30.596 --> 21:32.164
I hope you don't think
I'm rushing things.

21:32.164 --> 21:33.232
I do not.

21:33.232 --> 21:34.600
You conquered New York.

21:34.600 --> 21:36.736
Now it's time
to conquer Newport.

21:36.736 --> 21:38.538
But I haven't
conquered New York.

21:38.538 --> 21:40.673
What?
You go everywhere.

21:40.673 --> 21:43.442
- Oh.
- You dine in the best houses.

21:43.442 --> 21:46.512
You have a pew opposite
the Astors at St. Thomas.

21:46.512 --> 21:48.108
But I haven't got
a box at the opera.

21:48.108 --> 21:50.416
The Academy has
turned us down again.

21:50.416 --> 21:52.317
They can be very trying.

21:52.317 --> 21:53.748
Mrs. Astor can be
very trying.

21:53.748 --> 21:54.787
She must have known.

21:54.787 --> 21:57.060
Did she tell you
they were keeping us out?

22:00.295 --> 22:01.961
Do you think
the new Metropolitan Opera

22:01.961 --> 22:03.095
will succeed?

22:03.095 --> 22:04.496
The members
of the Academy are

22:04.496 --> 22:07.332
very determined it should not.

22:07.332 --> 22:09.301
And if you jump that way,

22:09.301 --> 22:11.671
you'll never take Mrs. Astor
with you.

22:11.671 --> 22:14.339
My advice would be
to stick with her.

22:14.339 --> 22:16.743
She'll get you into the Academy
in the end.

22:16.743 --> 22:18.844
I'm not much good
at "in the end."

22:18.844 --> 22:20.779
Besides, nothing stays
the same forever,

22:20.779 --> 22:23.317
and I can't always be
at Mrs. Astor's beck and call.

22:23.317 --> 22:25.585
Why not? I am.

22:25.585 --> 22:27.086
Aren't you coming in?

22:27.086 --> 22:33.692
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:33.692 --> 22:35.862
You see we've increased
the space in here

22:35.862 --> 22:37.864
and changed the angle
of the light.

22:37.864 --> 22:39.533
It's splendid.

22:39.533 --> 22:42.935
My son is a genius.

22:42.935 --> 22:46.372
We can use this room
for entertaining.

22:46.372 --> 22:48.641
Come look
into the old library next.

22:48.641 --> 22:52.979
It's worked even better
than I thought.

22:52.979 --> 22:55.147
You have done well, Larry.

22:55.147 --> 22:56.548
What will you do now?

22:56.548 --> 22:58.851
I expect I'll go to New York
and look for some work.

22:58.851 --> 23:01.754
I may have something
to suggest in that department.

23:01.754 --> 23:04.623
There is a widow
here in Newport

23:04.623 --> 23:08.027
who's planning some alterations
and additions to her house,

23:08.027 --> 23:09.796
a Mrs. Richard Blane.

23:09.796 --> 23:12.564
She's here?
Out of season? Why?

23:12.564 --> 23:14.668
She decided to live
in Newport

23:14.668 --> 23:16.903
after her husband's death.

23:16.903 --> 23:19.238
Has she been alone
for many years?

23:19.238 --> 23:22.208
He died about 18 months ago.

23:22.208 --> 23:24.076
Seems rather soon
for her to build.

23:24.076 --> 23:25.312
Isn't she still in mourning?

23:25.312 --> 23:26.845
Not exactly.

23:26.845 --> 23:30.482
But then the late Mr. Blane
was a good deal older.

23:30.482 --> 23:33.452
You mean she's glad
to be rid of him.

23:33.452 --> 23:35.788
Well, she's glad
to spend the money

23:35.788 --> 23:38.123
that he guarded like a hyena.

23:38.123 --> 23:39.591
[both laugh]

23:39.591 --> 23:41.495
I'm very grateful,
Mr. McAllister.

23:41.495 --> 23:43.195
You haven't met her yet,

23:43.195 --> 23:44.831
but I think
it could be managed.

23:44.831 --> 23:46.199
And you'd be in town
all summer.

23:46.199 --> 23:47.133
Mr. Russell.

23:47.133 --> 23:48.568
I'm just going up
to check the bedrooms

23:48.568 --> 23:50.139
before you see them.

23:53.274 --> 23:56.142
Tell me more
about Mrs. Blane.

23:56.142 --> 23:57.576
If you insist.

23:57.576 --> 24:00.245
She was penniless
and in a tricky situation

24:00.245 --> 24:01.947
when she met Mr. Blane.

24:01.947 --> 24:05.852
I do not believe she thought
he'd survive for 20 years.

24:05.852 --> 24:08.215
Well, why didn't she go
back to New York?

24:08.215 --> 24:12.091
Newport allows her
more... freedom.

24:12.091 --> 24:14.030
Hmm.

24:20.336 --> 24:21.534
Oh.

24:21.534 --> 24:23.102
Are you hungry?

24:23.102 --> 24:25.337
Dinner won't be long.

24:25.337 --> 24:27.439
Have you been crying again?

24:27.439 --> 24:28.975
Thinking about your father.

24:28.975 --> 24:30.843
We can't keep
torturing ourselves.

24:30.843 --> 24:35.515
I was thinking about
the first time I ever met him.

24:35.515 --> 24:37.717
He saved my life.

24:37.717 --> 24:39.985
Did I ever tell you that?

24:39.985 --> 24:42.587
No.

24:42.587 --> 24:44.157
I was walking home
from church,

24:44.157 --> 24:48.995
and two men started
following me, taunting me.

24:48.995 --> 24:51.996
- White men?
- Yes.

24:51.996 --> 24:55.701
And I rounded a corner hoping
to find somewhere to hide,

24:55.701 --> 24:58.505
and I practically ran
right into your father's arms.

24:58.505 --> 25:01.201
- Thank heavens.
- Mm-hmm.

25:01.201 --> 25:04.010
When the two men caught up
with me,

25:04.010 --> 25:07.780
Arthur stared them down.

25:07.780 --> 25:11.183
He didn't have to say a word,
and they ran off.

25:11.183 --> 25:12.652
<i>[somber music]</i>

25:12.652 --> 25:15.254
Your father later told me
that he--

25:15.254 --> 25:18.492
he saw what they were doing
and wanted to make sure

25:18.492 --> 25:21.461
that I got home unscathed.

25:21.461 --> 25:23.129
I never knew that.

25:23.129 --> 25:26.293
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:26.293 --> 25:29.536
I always felt so safe
with Arthur.

25:29.536 --> 25:32.938
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:32.938 --> 25:34.908
Sleep in a man's arms
for years,

25:34.908 --> 25:38.014
and you think you know him, but...

25:41.978 --> 25:43.215
There you are.

25:43.215 --> 25:44.818
[clears throat]

25:44.818 --> 25:49.288
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:49.288 --> 25:51.594
Dinner must be ready now.

25:55.163 --> 25:57.797
How did you hear
about my contretemps?

25:57.797 --> 26:01.766
Aurora Fane told me.

26:01.766 --> 26:04.904
Does your presence here mean
we're friends again?

26:04.904 --> 26:06.305
Oscar, you and I have
known each other

26:06.305 --> 26:08.941
far too long and much too well
not to be friends.

26:08.941 --> 26:12.015
If that is the case,
I'm delighted.

26:13.910 --> 26:15.981
Good.

26:15.981 --> 26:19.251
Now, will you tell me
what really happened?

26:19.251 --> 26:20.689
Nothing much.

26:26.761 --> 26:29.628
I saw you at church
that morning, by the way,

26:29.628 --> 26:33.065
with someone tall
and dark and handsome.

26:33.065 --> 26:34.837
Tell me.

26:36.637 --> 26:38.871
I met a guy in a bar,
and he said

26:38.871 --> 26:40.172
he had somewhere we could go.

26:40.172 --> 26:42.175
And so he took you
into a dark alley,

26:42.175 --> 26:43.508
and he beat you to a pulp,

26:43.508 --> 26:44.844
and he stole your wallet
and your watch?

26:44.844 --> 26:46.779
He didn't take my watch.

26:46.779 --> 26:47.947
I don't know why not.

26:47.947 --> 26:49.515
How long will this go on?

26:49.515 --> 26:52.546
You can't keep
putting yourself in danger.

26:52.546 --> 26:56.022
I'm starting to think
you may have a point.

26:56.022 --> 26:57.384
Meaning?

26:57.384 --> 26:58.891
I wonder if it isn't time
I began

26:58.891 --> 27:00.960
to live a more grown-up life.

27:00.960 --> 27:02.996
Don't tell me
this heralds the arrival

27:02.996 --> 27:06.531
of Oscar van Rhijn, family man
and pillar of society.

27:06.531 --> 27:09.002
His entrance is
rather overdue.

27:09.002 --> 27:10.603
You do know
you would be asking

27:10.603 --> 27:13.673
a very great deal of yourself.

27:13.673 --> 27:15.375
No more than thousands
of other men

27:15.375 --> 27:17.576
have asked before me.

27:17.576 --> 27:20.113
No more than you will
ask of yourself one day.

27:20.113 --> 27:22.214
Not me.

27:22.214 --> 27:24.517
I have no desire to lock
who I am in a box

27:24.517 --> 27:26.485
and throw away the key.

27:26.485 --> 27:28.287
I don't think I could anyway.

27:28.287 --> 27:29.622
And what will your life be?

27:29.622 --> 27:31.590
Friendship, companionship,

27:31.590 --> 27:33.459
perhaps something more
if I can learn to live

27:33.459 --> 27:35.327
with a little discretion.

27:35.327 --> 27:36.663
Still a life of lies.

27:36.663 --> 27:40.099
But I won't be
lying to myself.

27:40.099 --> 27:42.735
It's different for you.
You've got brothers.

27:42.735 --> 27:46.175
I am the torchbearer
of the House of Van Rhijn.

27:49.578 --> 27:50.879
Don't hate me.

27:52.847 --> 27:54.350
I will never hate you.

27:57.953 --> 28:01.387
[footsteps approaching]

28:01.387 --> 28:04.223
Mrs. Bauer thought you might
both like some coffee, sir.

28:04.223 --> 28:06.459
Oh, please thank her.

28:06.459 --> 28:09.429
<i>[light tense music]</i>

28:09.429 --> 28:10.563
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:10.563 --> 28:12.366
We'll manage for ourselves.

28:12.366 --> 28:17.704
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:17.704 --> 28:19.438
Did she see anything?

28:19.438 --> 28:22.075
There wasn't a lot to see.

28:22.075 --> 28:29.085
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:32.888 --> 28:34.319
Would you like anything else?

28:34.319 --> 28:36.022
Just coffee, thank you.

28:36.022 --> 28:38.091
It's good of you
to make time for me.

28:38.091 --> 28:39.158
Not at all.

28:39.158 --> 28:40.560
But I assume
you've come here on a mission.

28:40.560 --> 28:42.594
And you're right.

28:42.594 --> 28:44.830
I hope it wasn't
indiscreet of him,

28:44.830 --> 28:47.600
but our friend, Mr. McAllister,
seems to think

28:47.600 --> 28:49.535
that you're unhappy
that the Academy has

28:49.535 --> 28:50.970
failed to find a box for you.

28:50.970 --> 28:53.472
When one became available.

28:53.472 --> 28:58.010
But there are people on that
list who have waited forever.

28:58.010 --> 29:00.012
Your day will come, my dear.

29:00.012 --> 29:02.447
And the Academy of Music
has served

29:02.447 --> 29:04.884
New York society for 30 years.

29:04.884 --> 29:06.986
Have they not
earned our loyalty?

29:06.986 --> 29:08.487
Yours maybe, but not mine.

29:08.487 --> 29:10.123
Not when they won't let me in.

29:10.123 --> 29:11.991
Why didn't they see this coming
and build more boxes

29:11.991 --> 29:13.625
when there was still time?

29:13.625 --> 29:15.595
The Academy has been shortsighted.

29:15.595 --> 29:17.530
I'm told there are 120 boxes

29:17.530 --> 29:20.667
in the new
Metropolitan Opera House.

29:20.667 --> 29:22.635
They can't want it
to be exclusive.

29:22.635 --> 29:23.836
They'll fill them, though,

29:23.836 --> 29:27.206
with so many new people
in the city now.

29:27.206 --> 29:31.377
Mrs. Russell, you must know
how very proud I am

29:31.377 --> 29:32.945
of your success in New York.

29:32.945 --> 29:34.881
- That's generous.
- I mean it.

29:34.881 --> 29:36.949
You worked to be accepted.

29:36.949 --> 29:40.019
And I do hope
that I was a help.

29:40.019 --> 29:42.288
You wouldn't want
to throw that all away

29:42.288 --> 29:45.224
and find yourself back where
you started, out on your ear.

29:45.224 --> 29:48.628
I suppose I'd like to go
where I'm valued,

29:48.628 --> 29:49.962
where people are friendly.

29:49.962 --> 29:51.898
Well, the audience
at the new opera house

29:51.898 --> 29:53.432
will be easy to meet.

29:53.432 --> 29:56.302
But you'll find that they
are hard to get rid of.

29:56.302 --> 29:58.737
Hmm.

29:58.737 --> 30:01.107
Why don't I give a dinner
of opera enthusiasts

30:01.107 --> 30:02.742
so we can discuss
the whole subject.

30:02.742 --> 30:03.943
Would you come?

30:03.943 --> 30:05.244
May I see a list
of the guests?

30:05.244 --> 30:06.540
When I have one.

30:06.540 --> 30:07.947
But give me a date
that works first.

30:07.947 --> 30:10.716
I need you there
to be my guide.

30:10.716 --> 30:13.118
I shall take it
very seriously.

30:13.118 --> 30:15.555
I wouldn't like
to see you pay the price

30:15.555 --> 30:17.223
for backing the losing side.

30:17.223 --> 30:19.391
Well, you're right about
one thing, Mrs. Astor.

30:19.391 --> 30:22.362
I certainly intend to find
myself on the winning side.

30:22.362 --> 30:26.065
[laughs]

30:26.065 --> 30:29.803
Hiding his picture away
won't get rid of the pain.

30:29.803 --> 30:30.936
Of course not.

30:30.936 --> 30:32.972
But do you want
a daily reminder?

30:32.972 --> 30:36.508
Arthur, we had a grandchild!

30:36.508 --> 30:38.945
His photograph belongs
with the pictures of--

30:38.945 --> 30:41.981
of your parents and mine
and all the rest of them.

30:41.981 --> 30:44.117
They're dead,
but they're still our family.

30:44.117 --> 30:46.146
All right.
You want me to say it?

30:46.146 --> 30:47.186
I was wrong.

30:47.186 --> 30:49.589
I thought I was right,
but I was wrong.

30:49.589 --> 30:51.227
We should have kept the boy.

30:56.599 --> 30:57.797
There.

30:57.797 --> 30:58.964
Are you satisfied?

30:58.964 --> 31:02.569
How can I be satisfied?

31:02.569 --> 31:05.141
My grandson is dead.

31:08.543 --> 31:10.470
Oh.

31:10.470 --> 31:13.549
Uh, we saved you some dinner.

31:15.049 --> 31:17.186
I'm not hungry.

31:19.487 --> 31:22.788
He looks so much like you
at that age.

31:22.788 --> 31:25.124
[crying]

31:25.124 --> 31:28.695
Shall we keep it in here?

31:28.695 --> 31:32.632
<i>[somber music]</i>

31:32.632 --> 31:34.734
I don't think so.

31:34.734 --> 31:36.170
I'll have it in my room.

31:36.170 --> 31:38.971
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:38.971 --> 31:41.508
She doesn't want it
on display, Dorothy.

31:41.508 --> 31:45.478
She doesn't, or you don't?

31:45.478 --> 31:47.613
I lie awake at night

31:47.613 --> 31:52.785
thinking about how I should
have done things differently.

31:52.785 --> 31:55.822
I'm sorry.

31:55.822 --> 31:57.823
That's all I can say.

31:57.823 --> 31:59.292
Well, you just have
to keep saying it

31:59.292 --> 32:01.827
until Peggy can find it
in her heart to forgive you.

32:01.827 --> 32:03.563
Or I do.

32:03.563 --> 32:05.865
But don't you see?

32:05.865 --> 32:07.333
Even if you are sorry--

32:07.333 --> 32:10.937
and I do believe that you are--

32:10.937 --> 32:12.508
it doesn't change anything.

32:16.377 --> 32:18.845
So you'll hate me
all your life?

32:18.845 --> 32:21.848
I don't hate you.

32:21.848 --> 32:25.617
Look, we need a rest
from each other.

32:25.617 --> 32:30.490
We have been trapped in this
trio of regret for too long.

32:30.490 --> 32:32.359
Now I'm going to bed.

32:32.359 --> 32:37.697
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:37.697 --> 32:39.599
[whistles]

32:39.599 --> 32:43.235
<i>[bright music]</i>

32:43.235 --> 32:44.937
How I wish you would stay.

32:44.937 --> 32:46.940
It feels much too soon.

32:46.940 --> 32:48.808
I do worry so.

32:48.808 --> 32:50.777
You won't go back
to the bank today.

32:50.777 --> 32:54.246
I said
I'll be there next week.

32:54.246 --> 32:55.915
Marian, look after him.

32:55.915 --> 32:57.484
I will.

32:57.484 --> 33:04.493
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:05.894 --> 33:08.294
How are you, really?

33:08.294 --> 33:11.130
I'm making progress,
as they say.

33:11.130 --> 33:12.932
It could have been
so much worse.

33:12.932 --> 33:14.061
Indeed.

33:14.061 --> 33:15.902
I could have been killed,
and then what would have been

33:15.902 --> 33:17.136
the point
of my having lived at all?

33:17.136 --> 33:20.039
Oh, don't say that.

33:20.039 --> 33:22.742
Oh, look, a luncheon party.

33:22.742 --> 33:24.776
No doubt to which
I am not invited.

33:24.776 --> 33:27.313
Don't tell me you're still
pining for Gladys Russell.

33:27.313 --> 33:29.381
I suppose she's now
the cynosure of all eyes.

33:29.381 --> 33:31.450
Of course.
She's pretty. She's rich.

33:31.450 --> 33:33.686
She's out in society.
And this is New York.

33:33.686 --> 33:35.722
But are you still a contender?

33:35.722 --> 33:37.624
Haven't you given up?

33:37.624 --> 33:39.124
I should, really.

33:39.124 --> 33:40.459
She never answers my letters.

33:40.459 --> 33:43.129
And if we do meet,
it's very stilted.

33:43.129 --> 33:45.397
I'm sure Mrs. Russell has
told her not to speak to me.

33:45.397 --> 33:47.399
Well, if you're
really in love with her,

33:47.399 --> 33:49.168
you must give it another try.

33:49.168 --> 33:52.772
But this time,
make a proper plan.

33:52.772 --> 33:54.577
You fill me with resolve.

33:57.512 --> 34:01.481
So have you told your aunts
your secret yet?

34:01.481 --> 34:03.550
No, but I will.

34:03.550 --> 34:05.051
When?

34:05.051 --> 34:06.652
When I can't keep it secret
any longer.

34:06.652 --> 34:08.121
[both laugh]

34:08.121 --> 34:10.524
But what about you?

34:10.524 --> 34:12.825
[sighs]

34:12.825 --> 34:14.193
I just don't know
how much longer

34:14.193 --> 34:16.730
I can stay with my parents.

34:16.730 --> 34:19.265
What's the remedy?

34:19.265 --> 34:22.634
Is there any chance I could
come back to 61st Street?

34:22.634 --> 34:25.071
If Mrs. Van Rhijn hasn't
found a replacement.

34:25.071 --> 34:26.671
I assure you, she has not.

34:26.671 --> 34:28.640
Then can you ask her
if she'd meet with me?

34:28.640 --> 34:30.777
Aunt Agnes would welcome you
back with open arms,

34:30.777 --> 34:33.145
and so would I.

34:33.145 --> 34:36.748
Not everyone in that house
is so hospitable.

34:36.748 --> 34:38.985
I think Aunt Agnes regrets
keeping Armstrong

34:38.985 --> 34:41.153
when she let you go.

34:41.153 --> 34:44.290
If you think you can
handle her, please come back.

34:44.290 --> 34:48.127
I'd like to,
Miss Armstrong notwithstanding.

34:48.127 --> 34:50.463
I'll speak to Aunt Agnes
and write to you.

34:50.463 --> 34:51.834
Thank you.

34:53.769 --> 34:55.267
But why do you need my help?

34:55.267 --> 34:56.997
You know Gladys Russell.

34:56.997 --> 34:58.537
Why can't you arrange
to meet her yourself?

34:58.537 --> 35:01.440
Because her mother
doesn't want me as a suitor.

35:01.440 --> 35:04.443
Mrs. Russell doesn't like
any man she hasn't chosen.

35:04.443 --> 35:07.013
But I don't see
what I can do about it.

35:07.013 --> 35:08.313
Now, would you like
some more coffee,

35:08.313 --> 35:10.484
or can I fetch you a sandwich?

35:10.484 --> 35:12.852
I'll do it.

35:12.852 --> 35:14.286
I'm glad to see
you're better.

35:14.286 --> 35:15.824
Was it very terrible?

35:18.326 --> 35:20.426
It certainly made me think.

35:20.426 --> 35:22.627
What was I doing,
wandering around New York

35:22.627 --> 35:25.532
when I should have been
at home, dining with my family?

35:25.532 --> 35:26.465
Heavens.

35:26.465 --> 35:29.636
You mean you'd like
to settle down?

35:29.636 --> 35:32.171
I suppose I do.

35:32.171 --> 35:34.106
Which brings us
back to Miss Russell.

35:34.106 --> 35:35.707
Please help me.

35:35.707 --> 35:38.177
I've helped you before,
and nothing came of it.

35:38.177 --> 35:39.612
This time I know what to do.

35:39.612 --> 35:42.048
I just need a few minutes
alone with her.

35:42.048 --> 35:43.516
Ask us both to luncheon.

35:43.516 --> 35:44.679
No.

35:44.679 --> 35:47.086
That would be too obvious.

35:47.086 --> 35:48.922
But I've been meaning to mark

35:48.922 --> 35:50.857
Cousin Dashiell's return
to New York.

35:50.857 --> 35:52.391
You can come to that.

35:52.391 --> 35:53.625
What reason can you have

35:53.625 --> 35:55.261
for asking Gladys
but not her mother?

35:55.261 --> 35:57.263
Leave it with me.

35:57.263 --> 35:59.265
I have an idea.

35:59.265 --> 36:01.533
Mrs. Fane is throwing
a party for her cousin.

36:01.533 --> 36:03.969
What's wrong with that?
- It's on the day of my dinner.

36:03.969 --> 36:05.504
How could she do such a thing?

36:05.504 --> 36:07.973
Perhaps Mr. Montgomery
couldn't manage another date.

36:07.973 --> 36:09.708
It starts at half past 3:00.

36:09.708 --> 36:11.744
We'll be home before 6:00 with
plenty of time to get ready.

36:11.744 --> 36:13.040
I can't come.

36:13.040 --> 36:14.580
I won't be able to leave
the house that day.

36:14.580 --> 36:16.115
Then Gladys can go
with Miss Brook.

36:16.115 --> 36:17.350
She'll have been invited.

36:17.350 --> 36:18.450
But will Miss Brook
protect her

36:18.450 --> 36:19.651
from men I don't approve of?

36:19.651 --> 36:21.521
Honestly, Mother,
you say I'm not to speak

36:21.521 --> 36:22.883
to men you don't approve of,

36:22.883 --> 36:24.624
but you don't approve
of anyone.

36:24.624 --> 36:27.059
She must be allowed
to go out.

36:27.059 --> 36:28.995
You can't keep her
in a bandbox.

36:28.995 --> 36:30.830
[sighs] Oh, very well.

36:30.830 --> 36:33.165
I give in.

36:33.165 --> 36:34.433
Thank you.

36:34.433 --> 36:36.301
Do I have to be
at the dinner?

36:36.301 --> 36:38.104
Only I have some troublesome
business in Pittsburgh

36:38.104 --> 36:39.105
I'm dealing with.

36:39.105 --> 36:40.506
I need you there.

36:40.506 --> 36:43.443
I wish I could understand
the whole thing.

36:43.443 --> 36:45.211
You don't even like opera.

36:45.211 --> 36:47.213
Not so I've ever noticed.
- [scoffs]

36:47.213 --> 36:49.014
George,
the opera is where society

36:49.014 --> 36:50.382
puts itself on display.

36:50.382 --> 36:52.451
Not just in New York,
but all over Europe.

36:52.451 --> 36:54.949
And the leaders take boxes
where they meet each other

36:54.949 --> 36:56.255
and their children
court each other,

36:56.255 --> 36:58.557
and that is how
the wheels of society turn.

36:58.557 --> 37:00.860
The Academy tried to stop
the Metropolitan

37:00.860 --> 37:01.961
from being built.

37:01.961 --> 37:03.295
And they thought they could,

37:03.295 --> 37:05.064
but it'll be open
by the end of October.

37:05.064 --> 37:06.565
If you decide
to back the Met,

37:06.565 --> 37:08.568
you know you'll be
taking on Mrs. Astor.

37:08.568 --> 37:09.768
And?

37:09.768 --> 37:11.470
Of course I love
that you're not afraid of her.

37:11.470 --> 37:14.073
I'm glad to be her friend,
George, but not her lackey.

37:14.073 --> 37:17.043
<i>[light piano music]</i>

37:17.043 --> 37:18.344
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:18.344 --> 37:20.245
Aurora has written.

37:20.245 --> 37:23.149
She's giving a tea
for Cousin Dashiell.

37:23.149 --> 37:24.784
Weren't we going
to manage that?

37:24.784 --> 37:27.286
Aurora can do it.
She's his cousin.

37:27.286 --> 37:29.088
We'll all go,
and Marian can meet

37:29.088 --> 37:30.589
some more
suitable young people.

37:30.589 --> 37:32.859
Although I'm never sure that
your definition of suitable

37:32.859 --> 37:34.060
is quite the same as mine.

37:34.060 --> 37:37.196
If it isn't, it should be.

37:37.196 --> 37:41.000
I hope you're not still pining
after that tedious Mr. Raikes.

37:41.000 --> 37:42.501
Oh, Agnes.

37:42.501 --> 37:45.004
There's no need
to bring that up.

37:45.004 --> 37:46.405
Not really, Aunt Agnes.

37:46.405 --> 37:48.374
They were bound to marry
at some stage.

37:48.374 --> 37:50.509
All I hope is that next time,
you will listen to us

37:50.509 --> 37:52.344
and not assume we know nothing.

37:52.344 --> 37:56.115
I shall be more sensible,
if there is a next time.

37:56.115 --> 37:58.150
That's all we ask,
isn't it, Ada?

37:58.150 --> 37:59.685
Some respect for our advice.

37:59.685 --> 38:01.954
All I want is
for Marian to be happy.

38:01.954 --> 38:04.924
<i>[light music]</i>

38:04.924 --> 38:12.201
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:12.967 --> 38:16.069
I need you to confirm this is
the final list for ordering.

38:16.069 --> 38:18.170
Give it to me.

38:18.170 --> 38:19.839
How's it coming on?

38:19.839 --> 38:21.068
Will we be ready in time?

38:21.068 --> 38:23.142
I think so,
but planning is the key.

38:23.142 --> 38:24.809
I do have a favor to ask.

38:24.809 --> 38:27.446
As you know, Mrs. Russell hopes
to put on quite a show,

38:27.446 --> 38:29.815
so we're borrowing some footmen
from various households--

38:29.815 --> 38:31.751
And you want me
to swell their number.

38:31.751 --> 38:32.819
Not exactly.

38:32.819 --> 38:34.220
I don't mind.
It's part of my job.

38:34.220 --> 38:37.023
No, I need you
more as an underbutler

38:37.023 --> 38:38.724
to take care of the wines.

38:38.724 --> 38:40.292
We'll go through them together,
of course,

38:40.292 --> 38:42.395
but if you could see
to their opening,

38:42.395 --> 38:44.731
decanting, icing, and serving
throughout the evening--

38:44.731 --> 38:46.665
I'm flattered.

38:46.665 --> 38:48.902
But do you really think
that she'll side

38:48.902 --> 38:50.003
with the new Metropolitan?

38:50.003 --> 38:51.503
It's beginning
to look like it.

38:51.503 --> 38:53.405
Won't Mrs. Astor
kick up a stink?

38:53.405 --> 38:55.478
Mrs. Russell
doesn't lack courage.

38:56.778 --> 39:03.719
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:08.089 --> 39:09.188
Come with us!

39:09.188 --> 39:10.857
- Papa?
- Go on.

39:10.857 --> 39:13.696
[children giggling]

39:17.198 --> 39:21.134
Dashiell,
how very good to see you.

39:21.134 --> 39:22.769
Except you should have
called on us

39:22.769 --> 39:24.403
the moment you got to New York.

39:24.403 --> 39:26.339
Indeed I should have done,
Aunt Agnes.

39:26.339 --> 39:27.940
I hope you can forgive me.

39:27.940 --> 39:29.876
Oh, of course we can.

39:29.876 --> 39:32.011
Mwah. You know Oscar.

39:32.011 --> 39:33.579
Oscar, good heavens.

39:33.579 --> 39:35.815
We're both rather older
than when we last met.

39:35.815 --> 39:37.216
Don't remind me.

39:37.216 --> 39:39.285
And this is our niece,
Marian Brook,

39:39.285 --> 39:40.452
who lives with us now.

39:40.452 --> 39:42.254
Does that make us cousins?

39:42.254 --> 39:43.756
Almost, but not quite.

39:43.756 --> 39:46.259
Where is Frances?
Is she here?

39:46.259 --> 39:48.895
She is, but she found
a group of young,

39:48.895 --> 39:50.330
and so she escaped me.

39:50.330 --> 39:51.498
[laughter]

39:51.498 --> 39:54.467
Cousin Dashiell, welcome.

39:54.467 --> 39:56.402
Come. Shall we have our tea?

39:56.402 --> 39:57.873
Dashiell, good to see you.

40:02.010 --> 40:04.977
Oscar, why don't you
show Miss Russell

40:04.977 --> 40:06.278
Charles' new library?

40:06.278 --> 40:08.748
Ah, my pride and joy.

40:08.748 --> 40:09.916
Shall we?

40:09.916 --> 40:11.454
If you wish.

40:14.757 --> 40:16.422
I'm so pleased
you're well again.

40:16.422 --> 40:18.625
I'm not quite dancing yet,
but when I do,

40:18.625 --> 40:19.925
I hope you'll be my partner.

40:19.925 --> 40:20.993
Oh.

40:20.993 --> 40:22.222
Is your mother here?

40:22.222 --> 40:24.998
No.
Or I wouldn't dare talk to you.

40:24.998 --> 40:28.200
Then I'm glad she's not.

40:28.200 --> 40:31.437
Well, at least I know now why
you never answered my letters.

40:31.437 --> 40:33.139
Mother wouldn't see
that keeping them from me

40:33.139 --> 40:34.673
was wrong.

40:34.673 --> 40:37.776
I suppose she thinks
I don't have enough to offer.

40:37.776 --> 40:42.181
Which is why I asked Aurora
to give this party,

40:42.181 --> 40:43.983
so I could make
the offer myself.

40:43.983 --> 40:45.450
What?

40:45.450 --> 40:46.585
I know there are
men out there

40:46.585 --> 40:48.721
who are younger and richer
than I am,

40:48.721 --> 40:50.356
but we would live well.

40:50.356 --> 40:51.623
You could choose
your own friends,

40:51.623 --> 40:53.326
run your own house,
manage your own life.

40:53.326 --> 40:55.395
Isn't that what you want?
- Very much so.

40:55.395 --> 40:56.796
And I'm not a bully.

40:56.796 --> 40:59.031
I'd never force you
to echo my opinions

40:59.031 --> 41:00.500
and parrot all my views.

41:00.500 --> 41:01.968
Of course not.

41:01.968 --> 41:03.669
Most men would.

41:03.669 --> 41:05.337
That's true, I suppose.

41:05.337 --> 41:09.641
I am happy to be henpecked,

41:09.641 --> 41:12.412
as long as you're doing
the pecking.

41:12.412 --> 41:13.913
We'd have fun, Gladys.

41:13.913 --> 41:17.150
I know we would.
I want us to be happy.

41:17.150 --> 41:18.683
<i>[soft music]</i>

41:18.683 --> 41:21.421
Very happy.
And I believe we could be.

41:21.421 --> 41:25.825
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:25.825 --> 41:27.526
- I--
- Don't answer now.

41:27.526 --> 41:29.496
Just--just know that I love
and admire you

41:29.496 --> 41:30.897
more than I can say,

41:30.897 --> 41:33.366
more than I've ever felt
for any other woman.

41:33.366 --> 41:35.301
But you don't know me,
not really.

41:35.301 --> 41:38.637
I know you to be intelligent
and fine

41:38.637 --> 41:40.473
and independent
when you're allowed to be

41:40.473 --> 41:42.074
and witty.

41:42.074 --> 41:45.010
You have every quality
that I admire, truly.

41:45.010 --> 41:47.146
Shouldn't you be saying
these things to my father?

41:47.146 --> 41:48.448
I'll write to him.

41:48.448 --> 41:50.750
Oscar, Gladys.

41:50.750 --> 41:51.651
Oh.

41:51.651 --> 41:53.320
You mustn't miss the tea.

41:53.320 --> 41:55.791
Of course not.

41:58.426 --> 42:02.562
Gould, how are things going
with the Knights of Labor?

42:02.562 --> 42:04.158
Better for me than for them.

42:04.158 --> 42:05.665
I should expect nothing less.

42:05.665 --> 42:07.066
Their demands are outlandish.

42:07.066 --> 42:08.668
Their leader Powderly
says he wants

42:08.668 --> 42:10.570
all workers
to be in partnership

42:10.570 --> 42:11.971
with their employers.

42:11.971 --> 42:13.507
He can want
what he likes, Mr. Gould,

42:13.507 --> 42:14.640
but he won't get it.

42:14.640 --> 42:15.875
Have you sustained any damage?

42:15.875 --> 42:17.109
Have you?

42:17.109 --> 42:18.878
This isn't a competition, gentlemen.

42:18.878 --> 42:21.547
Mr. Gould is not
cornering the gold market.

42:21.547 --> 42:23.949
Mr. Russell is not
bankrupting a railroad.

42:23.949 --> 42:27.120
For once,
we're on the same side.

42:27.120 --> 42:28.254
He's right.

42:28.254 --> 42:31.090
Let us enjoy the sensation.

42:31.090 --> 42:33.527
They tried to target
my freight traffic

42:33.527 --> 42:34.827
and shut some down.

42:34.827 --> 42:37.296
- But you didn't give in.
- We can't give in!

42:37.296 --> 42:39.832
The list of what they want will
grow with every concession.

42:39.832 --> 42:43.236
Houses, medical care,
less work, more pay.

42:43.236 --> 42:45.805
They want an eight-hour
workday, for God's sake.

42:45.805 --> 42:47.406
And safety measures that make

42:47.406 --> 42:49.441
a child's nursery
look dangerous.

42:49.441 --> 42:51.443
The point is,
we can't back down,

42:51.443 --> 42:52.712
or we'll lose control
of everything

42:52.712 --> 42:54.581
we've spent our lives building.

42:54.581 --> 42:57.477
For once,
we must stand together

42:57.477 --> 43:00.219
and introduce change
when we decide, not them.

43:00.219 --> 43:03.355
They're a rabble,
so treat them like a rabble.

43:03.355 --> 43:05.558
If it comes to it, I'll hire
half the working class

43:05.558 --> 43:07.226
to kill the other half!

43:07.226 --> 43:09.629
<i>[tense music]</i>

43:09.629 --> 43:11.130
- Thank you.
- Goodbye, Aurora.

43:11.130 --> 43:12.231
And thank you both.

43:12.231 --> 43:13.465
This has been lovely.

43:13.465 --> 43:14.967
Everything was so charming.

43:14.967 --> 43:17.103
Oh, our pleasure.
We're so glad you could come.

43:17.103 --> 43:20.105
Aunt Agnes, could I hold you
back for one more minute?

43:20.105 --> 43:23.376
I have found Frances,
and she wants to say hello.

43:23.376 --> 43:25.577
How nice to see you, my dear.

43:25.577 --> 43:27.747
Aunt Agnes, Aunt Ada,
how are you?

43:27.747 --> 43:31.150
You've a good memory.
That's clear.

43:31.150 --> 43:33.485
Miss Brook,
what are you doing here?

43:33.485 --> 43:34.754
How do you know Miss Brook?

43:34.754 --> 43:37.491
Well, she's my teacher
at St. Mary's.

43:37.491 --> 43:39.058
What?

43:39.058 --> 43:41.461
I teach watercolors
at St. Mary's.

43:41.461 --> 43:45.131
<i>[quirky music]</i>

43:45.131 --> 43:46.732
On Thursdays.

43:46.732 --> 43:49.368
- The day is immaterial.
- [laughs]

43:49.368 --> 43:52.505
Did you know you were
teaching Dashiell's daughter?

43:52.505 --> 43:54.540
How could she?
We've only just met.

43:54.540 --> 43:56.175
Yes.

43:56.175 --> 43:57.977
We should go.

43:57.977 --> 43:59.613
But it's good to see you all.

43:59.613 --> 44:03.116
Come and call on us.

44:03.116 --> 44:05.619
So you and Mrs. Bauer would
have been on opposite sides

44:05.619 --> 44:07.186
of the war of 1866?

44:07.186 --> 44:10.756
Yes, I'm from Hanover,
which fought with Austria.

44:10.756 --> 44:13.959
And Miss Weber is from Berlin,
the capital of Prussia.

44:13.959 --> 44:15.661
Why can't Europe
be like America?

44:15.661 --> 44:17.963
Because Europe is
nothing like America.

44:17.963 --> 44:19.898
I hope you don't mind
my saying so,

44:19.898 --> 44:22.568
but you seem very young to be
a lady's maid to Mrs. Russell.

44:22.568 --> 44:24.604
I'm standing in
until she finds a new one.

44:24.604 --> 44:25.938
I'm Miss Gladys' maid.

44:25.938 --> 44:27.706
Now she's out
and enjoying the season,

44:27.706 --> 44:29.275
you must be dressing her
in glamorous ball gowns

44:29.275 --> 44:30.342
every night.

44:30.342 --> 44:32.611
Mrs. Russell keeps
her daughter on a tight rein.

44:32.611 --> 44:35.248
I suppose she's afraid
of fortune hunters.

44:35.248 --> 44:37.216
Of which there are
plenty in New York.

44:37.216 --> 44:38.452
Naming no names.

44:38.452 --> 44:40.186
[bell ringing]

44:40.186 --> 44:41.355
They're back.

44:41.355 --> 44:42.521
I better go.

44:42.521 --> 44:43.956
Thank you for my coffee,
Mrs. Bauer.

44:43.956 --> 44:45.958
Bye.

44:45.958 --> 44:47.461
I hope we meet again.

44:47.461 --> 44:50.063
I'd like that.

44:50.063 --> 44:54.366
St. Mary's is an old school
and very well respected.

44:54.366 --> 44:55.602
I don't care if it's where

44:55.602 --> 44:57.103
George Washington learned
to read.

44:57.103 --> 44:58.972
I teach nice young ladies
to paint.

44:58.972 --> 45:00.339
What could be more respectable?

45:00.339 --> 45:02.408
If you thought so, then why
did you keep it a secret?

45:02.408 --> 45:04.010
Because I knew
you'd be angry.

45:04.010 --> 45:05.745
Ada, why didn't you stop her?

45:05.745 --> 45:07.112
Me? What could I have done?

45:07.112 --> 45:08.648
When did you find out
about it?

45:08.648 --> 45:10.316
This afternoon, like you.

45:10.316 --> 45:13.085
So your contempt for us both
was at least consistent.

45:13.085 --> 45:15.720
I don't have contempt
for anyone.

45:15.720 --> 45:17.923
And it doesn't seem
to bother Cousin Dashiell

45:17.923 --> 45:20.225
that I teach at his
daughter's school, or Aurora.

45:20.225 --> 45:22.529
They feel sorry for you.
That's all.

45:22.529 --> 45:25.765
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

45:25.765 --> 45:27.266
You're wrong.

45:27.266 --> 45:30.130
Not everyone is as cruel
and mean-spirited as you.

45:30.130 --> 45:31.470
- Oh?
- Marian!

45:31.470 --> 45:33.706
Is it cruel to mind it
when you stamp on our name

45:33.706 --> 45:35.274
and drag it in the mud?

45:35.274 --> 45:37.211
Now, get out of my way!

45:37.211 --> 45:42.882
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:42.882 --> 45:46.253
I suppose
you have to drop it now.

45:46.253 --> 45:47.619
No, I won't.

45:47.619 --> 45:48.888
I've given my word
to the headmistress,

45:48.888 --> 45:50.450
and I'm not going to break it.

45:50.450 --> 45:52.225
Then things may
be uncomfortable.

45:52.225 --> 45:54.427
So what?

45:54.427 --> 45:57.096
I won't be put in a cage!

45:57.096 --> 46:02.001
<i>♪ ♪</i>

46:02.001 --> 46:04.170
Is everything all right,
Miss Ada?

46:04.170 --> 46:05.471
Yes, Bannister.

46:05.471 --> 46:07.874
Only I heard shouting,
which is unusual in this house.

46:07.874 --> 46:10.910
It--it was unusual, yes.

46:10.910 --> 46:15.214
But every now and then,
I wonder if it isn't good

46:15.214 --> 46:20.123
to shout a little
and let off steam.

46:22.791 --> 46:26.058
<i>[light music]</i>

46:26.058 --> 46:27.587
You sent for me, ma'am?

46:27.587 --> 46:29.128
I should be changing,
but I need you

46:29.128 --> 46:30.695
to tell me that everything's
taken care of.

46:30.695 --> 46:32.531
Everything is
taken care of, ma'am.

46:32.531 --> 46:35.134
We did a dry run the night that
you dined with Mrs. Cushing.

46:35.134 --> 46:37.270
And the deliveries?
The extra footmen?

46:37.270 --> 46:38.103
They've all arrived?

46:38.103 --> 46:39.706
Madam, please go up
and change

46:39.706 --> 46:41.544
and leave this to me.

46:44.179 --> 46:46.846
I am such a fool
to have agreed to a soufflé.

46:46.846 --> 46:48.675
We'll have to keep making
new batches

46:48.675 --> 46:50.983
at ten-minute intervals,
then only serve them

46:50.983 --> 46:53.419
as they're wanted
and throw the rest away.

46:53.419 --> 46:54.854
Mr. Watson, are you ready?

46:54.854 --> 46:56.088
I think so.

46:56.088 --> 46:57.724
I may have decanted
too much of the claret,

46:57.724 --> 46:59.258
but better too much
than too little.

46:59.258 --> 47:01.597
Mr. Church,
I'm doing a final check.

47:06.602 --> 47:09.536
How nice you look.

47:09.536 --> 47:10.436
I'd say that I fear

47:10.436 --> 47:13.072
it may harm you to be seen
in that company,

47:13.072 --> 47:14.940
but I know
you will only think me cruel

47:14.940 --> 47:16.512
and mean-spirited.

47:18.646 --> 47:20.480
Marian didn't mean
what she said.

47:20.480 --> 47:23.583
Really?

47:23.583 --> 47:24.818
I spoke too harshly.

47:24.818 --> 47:28.621
I admit that.

47:28.621 --> 47:32.558
Agnes is sorry too.
Aren't you?

47:32.558 --> 47:34.728
Bannister will escort you
across the street.

47:34.728 --> 47:41.938
<i>♪ ♪</i>

47:52.481 --> 47:55.849
[bell ringing]

47:55.849 --> 47:59.353
Miss Marian Brook.

47:59.353 --> 48:00.520
Isn't she lovely?

48:00.520 --> 48:02.021
Aurora, hello.

48:02.021 --> 48:03.255
Mr. Montgomery.
- Miss Brook.

48:03.255 --> 48:05.292
You never said
you were coming to this.

48:05.292 --> 48:06.693
He didn't know.

48:06.693 --> 48:08.160
But Charles was summoned
to Washington

48:08.160 --> 48:09.895
for a last-minute meeting tomorrow.

48:09.895 --> 48:11.363
I asked Dashiell
to take his place.

48:11.363 --> 48:12.998
I must say,
the Van Rhijn connection

48:12.998 --> 48:14.634
makes you all
into quite a club.

48:14.634 --> 48:16.168
Of which you are a member.

48:16.168 --> 48:18.738
By marriage, not by blood.

48:18.738 --> 48:20.239
Well, there's nothing
wrong with that.

48:20.239 --> 48:22.308
- Good evening, Miss Brook.
- Mrs. Russell.

48:22.308 --> 48:24.243
Gladys enjoyed
her tea with you.

48:24.243 --> 48:25.812
I'm sorry you couldn't come,

48:25.812 --> 48:27.780
but of course
I quite understand.

48:27.780 --> 48:30.016
Well, I've met
your cousin now anyway.

48:30.016 --> 48:31.484
Thank you
for letting me bring him.

48:31.484 --> 48:32.418
Nonsense.

48:32.418 --> 48:33.953
He saved me
from finding another man

48:33.953 --> 48:35.455
at the last moment.
[laughter]

48:35.455 --> 48:36.489
Charles was wretched.

48:36.489 --> 48:38.692
He says you have the best
French chef in New York.

48:38.692 --> 48:41.593
Oh, that's funnier
than you know.

48:41.593 --> 48:44.597
Is this dinner in aid
of the new opera house?

48:44.597 --> 48:45.965
Why do you say that?

48:45.965 --> 48:47.700
I thought it was
for opera lovers in general,

48:47.700 --> 48:49.368
but I see Mr. Gilbert's here.

48:49.368 --> 48:50.803
And isn't he in charge
of preaching

48:50.803 --> 48:52.539
the gospel of the Met?

48:52.539 --> 48:54.340
I suppose that's true.

48:54.340 --> 48:57.409
You do know I won't go
against Mrs. Astor.

48:57.409 --> 49:00.375
I know you think you won't,
but don't worry.

49:00.375 --> 49:02.014
We shan't fall out.

49:02.014 --> 49:05.785
Mr. and Mrs. Robert McNeil.

49:05.785 --> 49:07.186
Mr. Russell, good evening.

49:07.186 --> 49:10.457
Mr. McNeil. Mrs. McNeil.
How good of you to come.

49:10.457 --> 49:11.625
My daughter, Gladys.

49:11.625 --> 49:12.925
- How do you do?
- How do you do?

49:12.925 --> 49:15.260
- Gladys.
- Oh, please excuse me.

49:15.260 --> 49:17.362
I gather
Mr. Gilbert's presence means

49:17.362 --> 49:20.033
the dinner is to support
the Metropolitan?

49:20.033 --> 49:23.336
If so, count us in.

49:23.336 --> 49:24.937
Has he written
to your father yet?

49:24.937 --> 49:26.405
It was only this afternoon.

49:26.405 --> 49:27.807
What will you say
when he does?

49:27.807 --> 49:29.241
[sighs]
That depends.

49:29.241 --> 49:31.276
I want to get away
from my mother, of course.

49:31.276 --> 49:34.547
But do you really want
to be Mrs. Oscar van Rhijn?

49:34.547 --> 49:36.249
[both laugh]

49:36.249 --> 49:39.885
You do know that Mrs. Astor
would like the Metropolitan

49:39.885 --> 49:41.721
blown up from its foundations?

49:41.721 --> 49:43.655
Don't worry.
I have a plan.

49:43.655 --> 49:45.524
And this evening,
I simply want her to understand

49:45.524 --> 49:48.428
the competition
the Academy will face.

49:48.428 --> 49:50.029
Here she is.

49:50.029 --> 49:51.864
Mrs. Astor,
thank you for coming.

49:51.864 --> 49:53.232
I'm delighted to see you.

49:53.232 --> 49:55.869
You have guests
I wasn't expecting.

49:55.869 --> 49:59.038
You never said
you'd invited the McNeils.

49:59.038 --> 50:00.439
I'm afraid that they have spent

50:00.439 --> 50:02.509
a long time
on our waiting list,

50:02.509 --> 50:03.709
much longer than you.

50:03.709 --> 50:06.078
Several guests here have
spent time on your list.

50:06.078 --> 50:08.380
Have you combed the city
for the disenchanted rich

50:08.380 --> 50:10.116
who couldn't get a box
at the Academy?

50:10.116 --> 50:11.450
Oh, Mrs. Astor.

50:11.450 --> 50:13.352
The Academy Board may think
they can keep out

50:13.352 --> 50:15.221
the new people with impunity,
but you're clever enough

50:15.221 --> 50:16.588
to know they're wrong.

50:16.588 --> 50:18.691
While the Metropolitan would
welcome the old guard

50:18.691 --> 50:19.892
if they want to come.

50:19.892 --> 50:21.260
Why not take a box
in both houses

50:21.260 --> 50:23.329
and see how it plays out?

50:23.329 --> 50:25.932
Perhaps you do not
value loyalty.

50:25.932 --> 50:27.232
I am different.

50:27.232 --> 50:29.334
I should scold you, Mrs. Fish,

50:29.334 --> 50:31.704
but I know that you're just
playing with matches,

50:31.704 --> 50:32.905
as you like to do.

50:32.905 --> 50:34.541
Ah, may I present
Mr. Gilbert?

50:34.541 --> 50:35.542
Or do you know him?

50:35.542 --> 50:36.875
I know of him.

50:36.875 --> 50:39.346
He is in charge of grubbing up
the cash for the new house.

50:39.346 --> 50:40.246
[laughs]

50:40.246 --> 50:43.582
Not flattering, but true.

50:43.582 --> 50:46.185
I was hoping your presence here
was a sign

50:46.185 --> 50:47.452
you were open to argument.

50:47.452 --> 50:50.757
I am open
to fetching my coat.

50:50.757 --> 50:53.726
Where's Carrie?
- Oh.

50:53.726 --> 50:54.994
Please don't.

50:54.994 --> 50:56.929
We can't have a falling out
and be a story

50:56.929 --> 50:59.866
in the morning papers.

50:59.866 --> 51:02.935
If I stay,
it will be under duress

51:02.935 --> 51:05.171
and only to avoid a scandal.

51:05.171 --> 51:09.174
I shall be very grateful.

51:09.174 --> 51:11.110
Oh, look. We're going in.

51:11.110 --> 51:13.182
Mrs. Astor.

51:18.319 --> 51:21.487
<i>I must not delay
our no doubt excellent dinner.</i>

51:21.487 --> 51:24.123
But as a parting treat,
let me announce

51:24.123 --> 51:26.259
the singers we can
look forward to hearing

51:26.259 --> 51:28.193
in our first season.

51:28.193 --> 51:31.397
Sofia Scalchi,
Marcella Sembrich,

51:31.397 --> 51:34.200
Giuseppe Del Puente,
Andrea Romano,

51:34.200 --> 51:37.269
Italo Campanini,
Roberto Stagno,

51:37.269 --> 51:39.405
and of course,
the great Christina Nilsson...

51:39.405 --> 51:40.973
[crowd gasping]
Who will perform

51:40.973 --> 51:42.741
on the opening night.

51:42.741 --> 51:46.813
If any of you can sleep
after hearing those names,

51:46.813 --> 51:49.315
then I hope you dream of music.

51:49.315 --> 51:52.488
[muttering and laughter]

51:54.122 --> 51:58.090
But Nilsson always performs
at the Academy.

51:58.090 --> 52:00.392
The Academy is her home
in New York.

52:00.392 --> 52:03.196
She can't be singing.
- Well, she is.

52:03.196 --> 52:07.133
And surely even if they sell
every seat in the house,

52:07.133 --> 52:10.235
they won't have enough money
for that cast.

52:10.235 --> 52:12.038
They won't expect
to run at a profit

52:12.038 --> 52:13.673
for the first few years.

52:13.673 --> 52:15.041
I don't understand.

52:15.041 --> 52:16.175
What does that mean?

52:16.175 --> 52:17.543
I'd guess it means they have

52:17.543 --> 52:19.644
plenty of money
at their disposal.

52:19.644 --> 52:22.716
But they can't plan
to run at a loss.

52:22.716 --> 52:24.050
That isn't fair.

52:24.050 --> 52:25.584
Well, the audience
will have the chance

52:25.584 --> 52:27.921
to hear every major singer
in the world.

52:27.921 --> 52:29.892
Isn't that fair?

52:37.594 --> 52:39.435
[gate creaks]

52:44.238 --> 52:47.807
What are you doing?

52:47.807 --> 52:49.809
Just thinking.

52:49.809 --> 52:51.544
About Miss Weber?

52:51.544 --> 52:52.879
What are you talking about?

52:52.879 --> 52:54.483
You like her.

52:56.084 --> 52:57.783
Are you making plans?

52:57.783 --> 52:59.488
No.

53:00.655 --> 53:03.455
But I won't be a footman
all my life.

53:03.455 --> 53:05.358
And what would you like
to do?

53:05.358 --> 53:06.925
I'm interested
in a lot of things,

53:06.925 --> 53:11.892
but I'm not sure how to turn
any of them into a living.

53:11.892 --> 53:13.394
Perhaps Miss Weber
could help.

53:13.394 --> 53:14.867
Eh.

53:14.867 --> 53:16.940
I'm going inside. It's cold.

53:23.078 --> 53:28.647
<i>♪ ♪</i>

53:28.647 --> 53:31.317
So you feel
the Academy is finished?

53:31.317 --> 53:34.319
It seems to me the Academy
wants it every which way.

53:34.319 --> 53:36.021
They refuse
to build more boxes,

53:36.021 --> 53:39.291
and they won't spend the money
to secure the best singers.

53:39.291 --> 53:42.162
But they don't want
anyone else to do so either.

53:42.162 --> 53:44.229
[gasps]

53:44.229 --> 53:47.734
Mrs. McNeil,
are you all right?

53:47.734 --> 53:50.770
Flora? What is it?

53:50.770 --> 53:52.338
Nothing.

53:52.338 --> 53:56.142
That is, I must have bitten
my tongue or something.

53:56.142 --> 53:58.043
Or something?

53:58.043 --> 53:59.979
I bit my tongue.

53:59.979 --> 54:01.314
Hmm.

54:01.314 --> 54:05.051
<i>[quirky music]</i>

54:05.051 --> 54:06.485
Mrs. Brown, what do you think

54:06.485 --> 54:08.688
of our choice of cast
for the season?

54:08.688 --> 54:10.589
Tremendous.

54:10.589 --> 54:14.227
Yes, Mrs. McNeil is also
an admirer,

54:14.227 --> 54:16.296
aren't you, my dear?

54:16.296 --> 54:17.396
Aren't I what?

54:17.396 --> 54:19.666
An admirer of Roberto Stagno.

54:19.666 --> 54:21.200
What?

54:21.200 --> 54:25.738
The tenor? You admire him.

54:25.738 --> 54:27.735
Hmm?

54:27.735 --> 54:30.413
I suppose I do, yes.

54:42.224 --> 54:43.689
I hope it is not
a disappointment

54:43.689 --> 54:45.724
that we won't leave
the gentlemen to their port.

54:45.724 --> 54:48.723
Instead, would you like
to join me in the hall?

54:48.723 --> 54:51.700
[indistinct chatter]

54:57.305 --> 55:00.240
<i>[tense music]</i>

55:00.240 --> 55:06.778
<i>♪ ♪</i>

55:06.778 --> 55:09.015
Who was that?
Why were you looking at him?

55:09.015 --> 55:12.151
That man is my father.

55:12.151 --> 55:13.986
Did you know
he was a servant?

55:13.986 --> 55:15.721
My mother said he had
come down in the world,

55:15.721 --> 55:17.589
but I wasn't sure
her account was honest.

55:17.589 --> 55:20.626
How did you recognize him
after all this time?

55:20.626 --> 55:22.261
He used to come to the house
and watch me

55:22.261 --> 55:23.295
from across the street.

55:23.295 --> 55:25.865
When at last I asked why,
he told me.

55:25.865 --> 55:27.934
What can we do?

55:27.934 --> 55:31.370
Except hope it doesn't get out,
I suppose.

55:31.370 --> 55:33.707
Oh, I think we can do
more than that.

55:33.707 --> 55:37.511
<i>♪ ♪</i>

55:37.511 --> 55:40.683
[indistinct chatter]

55:42.317 --> 55:45.318
[guests gasping]
- Oh, my...

55:45.318 --> 55:47.954
- How?
- It's extraordinary!

55:47.954 --> 55:50.023
[laughter]

55:50.023 --> 55:53.026
<i>[uplifting music]</i>

55:53.026 --> 55:54.293
<i>♪ ♪</i>

55:54.293 --> 55:56.095
When was this all done?

55:56.095 --> 55:57.964
During dinner.
When do you think?

55:57.964 --> 56:00.803
But that's impossible.

56:02.832 --> 56:06.338
It's beautiful.

56:06.338 --> 56:08.274
You know now
that the new opera house

56:08.274 --> 56:09.943
will open in October
with a production

56:09.943 --> 56:11.144
of Gounod's "Faust."

56:11.144 --> 56:12.912
And as you heard,
we're lucky enough

56:12.912 --> 56:14.647
that Miss Christina Nilsson
will sing

56:14.647 --> 56:16.476
the part of Marguerite.

56:16.476 --> 56:18.851
But we are perhaps even luckier
than that this evening,

56:18.851 --> 56:21.453
because Miss Nilsson
has traveled to New York

56:21.453 --> 56:23.222
to give you a taste
of things to come.

56:23.222 --> 56:24.791
[crowd clamoring]

56:24.791 --> 56:26.558
What?

56:26.558 --> 56:30.397
I bid you welcome
to Marguerite's garden.

56:30.397 --> 56:33.569
[applause]
- Oh!

56:40.842 --> 56:43.909
[bright orchestra music
playing]

56:43.909 --> 56:49.148
♪ ♪

56:49.148 --> 56:52.084
[singing in Italian]

56:52.084 --> 56:59.128
♪ ♪

57:43.232 --> 57:45.004
I begin to grasp your plan.

57:45.004 --> 57:46.872
And you seem to have won
the first battle.

57:46.872 --> 57:50.110
I intend to win the war.
Now shh.

57:50.110 --> 57:57.120
♪ ♪

58:08.364 --> 58:15.499
<i>♪ ♪</i>

59:20.434 --> 59:22.638
[bright tone]
